# API Development Guidelines

This document outlines best practices for developing modern APIs with TypeScript, Node.js, and related technologies.

## Key Principles for API Design

- Write clean, consistent, and well-documented API endpoints
- Use RESTful or GraphQL principles with standardized patterns
- Apply modular architecture to enhance maintainability and reusability
- Use descriptive naming with proper HTTP verbs (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH)
- Structure API files consistently: route definitions, controllers, validation, business logic

## Project Structure Example

- A typical API project can be structured in a monorepo pattern:
  - `apps/api/` contains the main API service
  - `apps/web/` contains any client applications consuming the API
- Packages for shared code:
  - `packages/api-client` for typed API client libraries
  - `packages/auth` for authentication and authorization logic
  - `packages/database` for database schema and models
  - `packages/validation` for shared request/response validation
  - `packages/logger` for logging infrastructure
  - `packages/utils` for common utilities

## API Naming Conventions

- Use clear, consistent resource naming (plural nouns for collections)
- Follow RESTful conventions for endpoints structure
- Version APIs appropriately (/api/v1/resources)

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use TypeScript for type safety across your entire API stack
- Define interfaces/types for all request bodies, response payloads, and database entities
- Use discriminated unions for complex type relationships
- Create reusable type utilities to minimize duplication

## API Security Considerations

- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Validate all incoming data with schema validation (zod, joi, etc.)
- Apply rate limiting and other API protection measures
- Use HTTPS and proper security headers
- Follow OWASP API security guidelines

## Performance Optimization

- Implement efficient database queries
- Use proper indexing strategies for database collections
- Apply caching where appropriate (Redis, in-memory, CDN)
- Consider pagination for large datasets
- Use connection pooling for database connections

## API Testing

- Write unit tests for business logic
- Create integration tests for API endpoints
- Use automated tools for security testing
- Implement contract testing for API consumers
- Set up continuous integration with automated test suites

## Database Practices

- Define clear data models with proper relationships
- Use migrations for schema changes
- Implement data validation at database level when possible
- Consider using an ORM for type safety
- Structure database access in repository pattern

## Documentation

- Generate API documentation from code (OpenAPI/Swagger)
- Include examples for each endpoint
- Document error responses and codes
- Keep documentation in sync with implementation
- Consider developer experience when designing API interfaces

## Monitoring and Logging

- Implement structured logging for API requests
- Set up monitoring for API performance and uptime
- Track and alert on error rates and anomalies
- Use correlation IDs to trace requests across systems
- Collect metrics for API usage and performance
